---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { base } from '../../../utils/base.js';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import torinoRoadNetwork from '../../../assets/images/torino-road-network.png';

import ChoroplethFigure from '../../../components/ChoroplethFigure.astro';
import omiPrice from '../../../assets/images/omi-price.png';
import istatUnder5 from '../../../assets/images/istat-under5.png';
import istat2545 from '../../../assets/images/istat-25-45.png';
---
<BaseLayout title="Torino: Relocation Suitability - Nico">
  <div class="page-container">
    <div class="case-study">
      <header class="case-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study — Urban Suitability</p>
        <h1>Finding a Home in a City We'd Never Seen</h1>
        <p class="intro">
          In mid-2025, my wife had three job offers in Italy. We flew from
          Brazil to visit each city before choosing, picked one, and came
          home to prepare the move. That offer then fell through over
          bureaucratic delays — by which point we'd already given up our
          apartment and were staying with family, waiting to leave. A second
          scouting trip wasn't an option, so when a new contract came
          through — this time for Torino, a city neither of us had ever
          seen — there was no way to visit it in person. With no time for
          fieldwork, I turned my GIS toolkit toward a personal problem:
          narrowing down a neighborhood, a nursery with availability, and an
          affordable apartment, entirely from spatial data, before arriving.
        </p>
        <p class="aside">
          I ended up calling it, only half-jokingly, the "Urban Suitability
          Re-location" project.
        </p>
       
      </header>
    </div>

    <figure class="hero-split">
      <Image
        src={torinoRoadNetwork}
        alt="Road network of Torino, color-coded by hierarchy"
        widths={[400, 800, 1200]}
        sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 60vw"
        format="webp"
        quality={80}
      />
      <div class="hero-text">
        <h2>Torino: Road Network</h2>
        <p>The road network extracted for this project — the same graph later weighted for driving and walking analysis.</p>
      </div>
    </figure>
    <figcaption class="map-source">Data: © OpenStreetMap contributors</figcaption>

    <div class="case-study">
      <section class="methodology">

        <article class="step">
        <h2>1. Getting to know a city we'd never visited</h2>
        <p>
          Before anything quantitative, I used ISTAT census data — age
          brackets, foreign-resident share, education level — to look for
          areas where the resident population resembled our own profile:
          young families in a similar age range, rather than a generic
          demographic snapshot of the city. Together with OMI zone price
          data, this became a set of independent choropleth maps, not a
          combined score — an exploratory read aimed at that specific
          question. Classes were defined with quantile and Jenks natural
          breaks, tested in parallel, since equal-interval classes failed
          to surface meaningful spatial variation in the data.
        </p>
        <div class="choropleth-grid">
          <ChoroplethFigure
            img={omiPrice}
            alt="Estimated monthly rent for an 80m² apartment, by OMI zone, Torino"
            title="Estimated rent — 80m² apartment (OMI zones)"
            legend={[
              { color: '#D9AE4E', label: '< €664' },
              { color: '#C67A2E', label: '€664–784' },
              { color: '#A8442A', label: '€784–1,000' },
              { color: '#7A2033', label: '> €1,000' },
            ]}
          />
          <ChoroplethFigure
            img={istatUnder5}
            alt="ISTAT under-5 population share, Torino"
            title="Population under 5 (%)"
            legend={[
              { color: '#C8D9C9', label: '< 2.2%' },
              { color: '#8FAE90', label: '2.2–6.9%' },
              { color: '#6B8C6E', label: '6.9–22.2%' },
              { color: '#4F6B52', label: '> 22.2%' },
            ]}
          />
          <ChoroplethFigure
            img={istat2545}
            alt="ISTAT population aged 25-45, Torino"
            title="Population aged 25–45 (%)"
            legend={[
              { color: '#C8D9C9', label: '< 10%' },
              { color: '#8FAE90', label: '10–26%' },
              { color: '#6B8C6E', label: '26–56%' },
              { color: '#4F6B52', label: '> 56%' },
            ]}
          />
        </div>
        <p>
          This pattern didn't point to a single obvious concentration.
          Neighborhoods with a strong 25–45 presence often showed very few
          young children — more consistent with student or early-career
          housing than with families like ours. Cross-referencing that
          against OMI rent data pointed our attention toward the city's
          semi-central zones, where the two profiles overlapped more
          closely.
        </p>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>2. Commute isochrones to three work sites</h2>
        <p>
          My wife's job involved regular travel to three sites outside
          Torino (Luserna San Giovanni, Aosta, Moncalieri), reachable only
          by car. I built the regional road network with OSMnx, assigning
          travel speed by road type (motorway / trunk / primary /
          secondary / tertiary / residential) since real-world speed data
          isn't consistently available per segment. For each site,
          QNEAT3's Iso-Area interpolation produced a continuous
          travel-time raster; the three were combined with Raster
          Calculator into several weighted weekly-commute scenarios,
          since visit frequency per site wasn't known in advance.
        </p>
        <p class="callout">
          <strong>Known limitation, stated deliberately:</strong> this
          treats the road network as undirected and doesn't account for
          one-way restrictions — adequate for regional-scale comparison,
          not for street-level routing.
        </p>
        <div class="image-placeholder">Combined commute raster / scenario table</div>
      </article>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>3. Local services and nursery availability</h2>
        <p>
          OpenStreetMap coverage for local services (nurseries, markets,
          gyms, playgrounds, pharmacies) proved too sparse compared to
          Google Places, so I queried the Places API directly — splitting
          the comune into sub-areas to stay under its per-query result
          cap — for both Torino and Pinerolo, then cleaned the resulting
          dataset (AOI filtering, duplicate removal) before loading it
          into PostGIS.
        </p>
        <p>
          For nurseries specifically, I contacted 100+ by email to ask
          about availability, updating status directly in PostGIS as
          responses came in.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>4. Walking-distance isochrones from available nurseries</h2>
        <p>
          Using the pedestrian network (OSM footways, also via OSMnx) and
          QNEAT3's Iso-Area tools (Contours and Polygons, from Layer), I
          mapped distance bands — 200 to 1200m in 200m increments — from
          nurseries with confirmed availability.
        </p>
        <p class="callout">
          <strong>A deliberate methodological choice:</strong> distance
          instead of time. Walking time with a toddler is too variable to
          be a reliable metric, so shortest-path distance was used
          instead of the fastest-path time model applied to the commute
          step above — a different metric for a different kind of
          movement.
        </p>
        <div class="image-placeholder">Distance-band map — nurseries</div>
      </article>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>5. Narrowing down to a shortlist of areas</h2>
        <p>
          Nursery proximity worked as a hard exclusion filter. The
          demographic context, service layers, and commute isochrones
          from steps 1–2 were then used as reference layers —
          cross-checked manually, not combined into a weighted overlay —
          to narrow the search to a handful of promising areas.
        </p>
        <p>
          Pinerolo, closer to two of the three work sites, was carried
          through this same process as a real alternative — and ruled
          out once the data showed too few nursery vacancies and
          apartment listings to work with.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>6. Manual listing search</h2>
        <p>
          Scraping immobiliare.it and idealista.it was ruled out for
          terms-of-service reasons, so listings within the shortlisted
          areas were searched manually, using each site's
          draw-a-search-area tool. Promising listings were digitized as
          points in the database, with attributes filled in by hand.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="step">
        <h2>7. Real monthly cost model</h2>
        <p>
          Listed price alone doesn't reflect real cost, so each candidate
          apartment was enriched — via follow-up contact — with
          condominium fees, heating, an electricity estimate, and parking
          (subscription or rental cost, where no spot was included).
          Nursery fees were added per listing based on the nearest
          available nursery. One-off costs — furnishing (for unfurnished
          units) and agency commission — were amortized over an assumed
          minimum one-year tenancy to produce a comparable monthly
          figure. Missing values were imputed with the average across the
          candidate set. The resulting ranking was used to prioritize
          which apartments to contact and visit first.
        </p>
        <div class="image-placeholder">Cost ranking — relative index</div>
      </article>

    </section>

    <section class="result">
      <h2>Result</h2>
      <p>
        We saw Torino for the first time the week we moved in — and
        within days had signed a lease on an apartment 800 meters from
        our daughter's nursery, in a neighborhood we'd only ever known
        through census tables, isochrone maps, and a spreadsheet of email
        replies.
      </p>
    </section>

    <a class="cta-button" href={`${base}/en/case-study-torino/technical/`}>
      Read the technical deep dive →
    </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-container {
    padding-left: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
    padding-top: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
    padding-bottom: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 2cm);
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .page-container {
      padding-left: 1.5rem;
      padding-top: 1.5rem;
      padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
  }  
  .case-study {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-brass);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .case-hero h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .intro, .step p, .result p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted-2);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .aside {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }
  .step {
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(198, 146, 20, 0.12);
  }
  .step h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
  }
  .callout {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-paper);
    background: var(--color-ink-light);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-brass);
    padding: 0.85rem 1.1rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }
  .image-placeholder {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    border: 1px dashed rgba(159, 173, 185, 0.4);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem 1rem;
    text-align: center;
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
  }
  .hero-image {
    padding: 4rem 1rem;
  }
  .result {
    margin: 3rem 0 2.5rem;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(198, 146, 20, 0.12);
  }
  .result h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-brass);
    margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
  }
  .cta-button {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    background: var(--color-brass);
    padding: 0.6rem 1.2rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .case-study {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .hero-split {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    margin: 2rem 0 0;
    max-width: 58rem;
  }
  .hero-split img {
    flex: 1 1 auto;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    min-width: 0;
    border-radius: 8px;
    display: block;
  }
  .hero-text {
    flex: 0 0 15rem;
    background: var(--color-paper);
    color: var(--color-ink);
    padding: 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
   @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .hero-split {
      flex-direction: column;
    }
    .hero-text {
      flex: 0 0 auto;
    }
  }
  .hero-text h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 0.65rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .hero-text p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .map-source {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .choropleth-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .choropleth-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
  
</style>